A constitutional DAO treats the DAO’s rules as a living, enforceable “constitution” — either hard-coded into smart contracts (“code as constitution”) or as a formal, amendable charter that governs behavior, proposals, voting, and enforcement. This goes beyond simple token-weighted voting (DAO 1.0) or modular upgrades (DAO 2.0). It creates DAO 3.0 structures: modular, relational, context-adaptive, and resilient to chaos while preserving high autonomy.
Key characteristics (from 2026 examples and analyses):

Formal charter or constitution ratified at launch (often by initial members or AI systems in agent-native cases).
Rule engine that checks every proposal/action against constitutional principles before execution.
Adaptive mechanisms — rules can evolve via weighted voting/quorum, but core protections (e.g., treasury safeguards, rights of “citizens”) require supermajorities or multi-step ratification.
Provence/auditability — every decision logs lineage (SHA-256 style or on-chain) for transparency.
Hybrid enforcement — smart contracts handle routine execution; human/AI fallback or arbitration for edge cases.

